This was our first visit for 2011. The last time we dined here we did the whole booking 3 months in advance routine. That meal as noted in my prior review was absolutely amazing. This time around, we had spent the day enjoying SF and we had happened to be walking around Ghirardelli Square when we jokingly said we should just "wing it" and walk into Gary Danko for dinner without any kind of reservation. After the initial laughter over the preposterousness of this brash idea...we both said why the heck not?! Dressed to the nines in my T-shirt and jeans, we strolled in and braced ourselves for denial of entry. Instead, we hit the jackpot and were promptly seated to the very last 2 seats at the bar. Since they serve their full menu at the bar, this worked out perfectly for us. Over the course of our 3-hr meal, we enjoyed every bite of the Roast Maine Lobster, Seared Filet, Branzini with Gnocchi and warm Louisiana Butter Cake. Thanks to the awesome bartender, our meal was complemented by an array of superb cocktails..including a particularly tasty Sidecar and Blood & Sand. All in all, we had a truly excellent spontaneous evening at Gary Danko. Again it reaffirmed our belief that this is our very favorite restaurant.

I've now been to Gary Danko a total of 3 times and been to at least 20 different Michelin-starred restaurants. Some of my favorite dishes were a hit or miss during follow-up visits, and as a result I am now updating my rating to a 4* instead of 5*. I have to reiterate, however, it is definitely still a place that's worthy of a visit (or more). Will be updating this review soon with more emphasis on the individual dishes.

Amazing service! Great food! Wife and I enjoyed every dish! And did I mention impeccable service?! Will visit again when in SF!

Gary Danko is a classic. As such you will have classics and feel classic. The menu and decor could use some updating. Or maybe not. Maybe that's the way they want it to be. And I'm fine with that too.

Top of the line in every way. 5 star food, service, wine, somellier. Can't say enough good things.

Was excited to try out this famous establishment, and I only had to reserve about a month in advance for a party for two! Granted, it was on a Monday at 5:30 p.m. but that worked. We were seated immediately with no wait. Service was great - people were always refilling our water, taking away our plates, cleaning the table, and checking up on us. Our waiter was also very nice and friendly - unlike some fancy restaurants with stiff/stuck up staff, the staff at Gary Danko's were friendly and didn't come off as snobbish at all. We each got the three course for $81 (I guess they raised their price recently). It's cool bc you can order three of anything on the menu - if you want three desserts, you can order three desserts. Or if you want three entrees, you can order three entrees. Just note that the chef will proportion the dishes out, though, so you won't get three full sized entrees if you order all entrees. Supposedly he has some kind of method, but it seemed to work bc we were really full by the end of our three courses. We got: -Amuse Bouche - Corn Soup - This was delicious! Wish I had a whole bowl instead of a few bites. -Scallops - Cooked very well with a pea sauce. Delicious! -Crispy Farm Egg w/ Grits and Pancetta - I loved the farm egg, which had a really crispy and light batter yet the inside was cooked perfectly for a soft boiled egg. Came with creamy grits and some bits of pancetta. -Soft Shelled Crab - Very crunchy and delicious. Came with mashed potatoes and some corn bits. -Bison - I was not a fan of this dish, though my friend had wanted to order it. I just don't like bison, I guess, though it was tender (and served rare). It came with the most delicious little cipollini onions, which were marinated in a vinegar sauce. OMG they were the best onions I've had. The cheesy green spatzle (type of small flour dumpling) was very good, too. -Duck Breast w/ Duck Hash - This entree was okay - the duck was very tender, though the hast was a bit salty. I'm not sure what it was, but the dish was just average. I think I expected a sweeter sauce, which is what I'm used to with duck. -Strawberry Souffle - They also offered a chocolate souffle on the menu, but I wanted to try the strawberry since I've never had it. It was seriously so light and fluffy, melting in our mouths. They know their souffles here. It came strawberry sauce and strawberry sorbet. -Tray of Mini Desserts - This was so cute! We got a tray of about 9 different bite-sized desserts. We were so full but we managed to finish them. :) Don't skip out on ordering their other desserts, though, or you'll be missing out! I even got a little pineapple cheese cake to take home with me. My friend, who is male, didnt, though, so I felt kinda bad for him. Oh, well! I guess only the women get to take one home, though I wonder what happens with there is a table of two men? I think everything but the main entrees were stellar. Though I wasn't a huge fan of the entrees we got, they were still solid. Bread was good as was the butter. We didn't finish a few bites of our entrees bc we were just too full, so I'm not sure what some reviewers are talking about when they complain about the portions. The decor is a little old-fashioned (not as modern as some) but it has been around for a long time, so it had a classic feel to it. My friend ordered a non-alcoholic drink (passion fruit) and it was served in a martini glass, so you couldn't tell it was non-alcoholic. My drink, which had was fruity and contained alcohol, was nice and refreshing. They had quite a selection of cocktails and wine to choose from. This place definitely deserves the Michelin Rated star!

I've only been to this PRISTINE EXPENSIVE restaurant once in my entire life. It was several years back, on my birthday. My brother had made reservations a few weeks prior to December 13th, because this place is very high in demand, despite the fact that it is VERY PRICEY up the ARSE! You literally get what you pay for, and my brother paid for it, so I was just a happy go lucky gal. It was just my mum, my bro, and myself. HOLY CRAP! As Peter Boyle, the late actor would always say on Everybody Loves Raymond. This stuff was HOLY... GREAT.... CRAP!... the great type of CRAP! It's like fare that's been blessed by some HOLY MOLY force that just melts and oozes in your mouth. Choose anything, blind folded or nose closed up, and your taste buds are all you need to feel like you're entering some heaven of unctuous medley of perfectly cooked fare. The ambiance is just killer. I feel like I'm in some palace of great walls of China, or a place that's part of the 7 wonders of the world type of vibe. The service of course is just timed neatly and precisely, like some choreographed dance that's been practiced to utter perfection. Even if it's fake, it's just nice, because the price is so expensive, that if the service missed a beat, they'll probably receive a silent beating at the end! :P It's my birthday, and this time I don't need to cry. I'm well taken care of, and I'm not the one to pay the bill! SWELL! The audience at this joint are indeed the upper class creme de le creme... I see grannies and grandpa's who look like they belong on the red carpet, with their huge gems and sparkly bracelets. Everyone looks like they're going to pose for the Hollywood lights and cameras, and they speak with such: 'Oh me oh my, this is just heavenly... Oh yes, we're going to the Hamptons this spring, and yes my son from Princeton will be joining us... Oh yes, England is on our list too! Ha ha ha!... Oh that's just divine! Where on earth did you buy such pearls!...' You know, conversations that you just don't hear everyday, unless you're always surrounded with such wealth. It's not that I don't appreciate the opportunity to eat at such pristine places, with plates filled with delicious artwork, it's just another world of the many worlds that exist today. I see and feel all the worlds out there, and it's just strangely amazing how one place, this circle we all live in, has such crazy disparities and similarities... as long as I keep focus on what truly matters, it gets easier for me to remain rooted within the one that matters the most. I suppose, I want and need to experience them all, to find what I'm truly seeking. All and all, I'm grateful that my brother made reservations at Gary Danko, because his intention was good... 'I love my sister, and I want her to see and eat and feel PRECIOUS.' So, even when dressed in my comfy sporty sweats, I got to eat and dine at one of the best! Go to Gary Danko at least once in your life, if you haven't yet!

** Part 2 of 2** (specific dish reviews) * Amuse-bouche: Cucumber tomato soup. - Delicious! Loved this. Great interplay of flavors, w/ a dallop of sour cream & chives, & some diced tomato/cucumber sauce in the middle. The tartness of the tomatoes went really well w/ the heavier cucumber puree soup (a slight sweet taste). * Glazed Oysters w/ Osetra Caviar, Zucchini & Lettuce Cream - Delicious! Loved this! I have never had more rich & flavorful oysters. They soak these in a specially made fish sauce (we questioned the hell out of the servers to figure out what in the world made these oysters so awesome). - The caviar added a much needed sharp contrast to the heavy, rich oysters & sauce (which were awesome - but you do need a counter to these flavors), being lighter & having a slight tang. * Risotto w/ Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Peas, Corn, & Roasted Tomatoes - A very impressive app. You get a giant helping & it's steaming hot when it comes out. The lobster is wonderful. - However for me personally, the risotto was a little undercooked (a personal issue. Both my friends thought it was perfect. I prefer it more mushy for lack of a better word, do go w/ the heavy/creamy texture of the dish as a whole. I'm just being picky though - this is quite a delicious app. * Seared Sonoma Foie Gras w/ Caramelized Red Onions & Cherries - The most well-balanced of the apps we had. - The caramelized onions give it a sharp tart flavor & the cherries a hint of sweetness. - Those countered well w/ the heaviness of the foie gras, which was perfectly seared w/ just a perfect hint of charring. * Seared Sea Scallops w/ Asparagus-Pea Puree, Pickled Radish, Spring Onions & Sauce Marechal - Really well done, a hint of charring yet raw in the middle, w/ a very tender & homogenous texture (my friend said this is the best scallops she's ever had. I believe her). - The sauce is savory while the peas & puree added a great sweetness. * Roast Main Lobster w/ Potato Puree, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn & Tarragon - Delicious!! Certainly a very heavy, creamy dish, & everything is wonderful - the potato puree is so smooth & the sauce is extremely rich. - I'm not usually a big fan of lobster but this dish definitely turned me around to that. The tail has a delectable crunch & the claw is so tender & soft. * Quail Stuffed w/ Foie Gras, Mushroom & quinoa, Braised artichokes, Peas, Prosciutto, & Olive Butter - First disappointment of the night. While everything sounds good on paper, I don't think the ingredients were balanced well or cooked to their best. - The mushroom was extremely heavy in flavor - there was way too much of this. There was not enough foie gras because all three of us could not taste it at all. There was too little quinoa, which could've added a great grainy texture to the filling, & it didn't add much to the dish. The prosciutto was steamed or something - no texture or much flavor to it. Sames goes to the artichokes, very lacking in flavor. - The quail itself probably had the best quality meat, being fairly tender & moist, of our three entrees. But it was ruined by all the other ingredients that really weren't balanced well. * Moroccan Spiced Squab w/ Raisins, Almonds, Chermoula & Orange-Cumin Carrots - Loved loved loved the sweet/nutty flavor of the stuffing. It tasted like delicious couscous & was wonderful. - However the meat was extremely gamey, & even though it was cooked rare to medium-rare, it was extremely tough to eat. They shouldve given us steak knives as this was extremely difficult to cut w/ regular table knives. - I should say that our server did recommend other dishes over this because of the very thing above - the meat being very tough & gamey & not for everyone. * Lemon Pepper Duck Breast w/ Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive & Cherries - GIANT disappointment. The duck was extremely dry & too tough. Once again we needed steak knives to cut apart the meat. - A big reason we chose this was for the lemon flavor, but we could not taste this at all! - The endives are steamed/boiled - soft & flavorless. The duck hash had a little more savory flavor & had more tender/moist meat, but really was nothing special. * Baked Chocolate Souffle w/ Two Sauces - This is apparently THE dessert to get, & it was good, but not extremely amazing. It's fairly light & SO fresh out of the oven that the heavy sauces kind of melt the insides of the cake so it dissolves into the sauce. The chocolate, while dark & good, totally overcomes the white (vanilla?) sauce so you can't taste nor see it. * Free: Lemon souffle cake (for our anniversary) - Now this was great! Loved the tart flavor of the lemon, that it was served cold, & the heavier yet jelly-like soft texture of the cake. * Free: Cookie sampler plate - Nice assortment - some good dark chocolates as well as lemony tart like items. *Free: Banana cake - LOVED it! Extremely moist, w/ a wonderful sweet cream cheese in the middle.

It's always a fun experience - basic food, kind of tame and safe. It was definitely edible no complaints - it was somewhat delicious. The ambiance had a nice basic vibe, servers were gentle. More Merican than French.

By far, one of my favorite restaurants. The food is always exceptional as well as the service. Whenever I'm in SF with my husband and/or celebrating a special occasion, I make it a priority to visit Gary Danko. Favorites include seafood dishes and the foie gras.

There's nothing bad to say about this restaurant...period. From start to finish this is the perfect restaurant. Let's start with the very beginning...trying to get a table...book way in advance! Although I booked 24 hours before because I was visiting SF for business...I lucked out, don't be me. If you're planning on coming to SF book it the moment you book your flight. They were extremely accommodating with adding an additional guest and there was no problem. Now, the food. The food is exquisite. The menu options plus the flexibility gives you the freedom to try whatever your heart desires. Not one person in our party had a bad meal. I had four courses and they were all perfectly executed. Finally, the service. The service is admirable. Waiters and staff are very attentive and "no" is not in their vocabulary. To top it all off they give you miniature desserts to take home with you when you get the check. Go now!

For my 800th review it was only fitting that I review Gary Danko (GD). I've gone by GD many times on the cable car on my way home in Russian Hill. I'll be honest and say that the Michelin star buzz is a bit beyond me. Over the years I have enjoyed some amazing restaurants in SF but this is my first time at a restaurant that is such an institution. My girlfriend was generous enough to take me here for my 30th birthday. It did seem that a good number of people dining were here for a special occasion. The first thing I noticed was that the service was superb. This is the one differentiator between restaurants with great food that are more reasonably priced. Everything at GD seemed perfectly choreographed and executed. It's the difference between a highly skilled NCAA division 1 athlete and an gold medal olympian. Both great but one has honed their craft to a remarkable degree. My favorite dish was the lobster risotto. One of the best dishes I have ever had. I also had the pork belly which I found to be above average but didn't blow away other pork belly I've had. I also enjoyed the scallops. Some of the best I've had. What I most liked about GD is that you have a 3, 4 and 5 course option and you get to decide what items you eat. While this seems to be common sense it has not been my experience dining in nicer restaurants; usually the courses are determined for you. The bread and butter to start were amazing. Simple but amazing. For the desserts we had the creme brulee trio and souffle. Both were excellent. What can I say that hasn't been said? Gary Danko is worth a visit for a special occasion. While you can cab or drive here, taking the cable car at night was a nice touch as it drops you off right in front. Thank you, Sofia H!

Ok. Second time around was much, much better than the first. Two birds with one stone. Wanted something special for the lady so decided to come here for a combined anniversary + early valentine's dinner lol. Made reservations a little more than a month in advance and the earliest opening on a Thursday night was for 9 PM. The reservation process was quick and easy and they called the week of the reservation to confirm. Was a little worried about getting rushed to finish dinner since the restaurant closes at 10, but we stayed until almost midnight and the staff were nothing but courteous. Parking was a breeze with multiple spaces open around the corner. Saved on the valet and the embarrassment of having them park my trusty but well aged civic. From the many yelp reviews we decided to do the four course option, but we were fairly stuffed by the time the third course came around, yet we savored and ate every single bite, including both souffles. Yes we got both of them haha. What we ordered: First Course Crispy Farm Egg Lobster Risotto Second Course Roast Maine Lobster Seared Sea Scallops Third Course Seared Filet of Beef Lemon Pepper Duck Breast Fourth Course Strawberry Souffle Chocolate Souffle Besides the souffles, the stars of the night were the lobster risotto and the scallops. This is hands down the best scallops I ever had, out shinning the ones at Alexander's. We were both disappointed by the crispy farm egg, especially when it was hyped up by so many reviews here. An odd note is that they give you a butter knife to cut the filet unless you specifically ask for a steak knife. At the end, the meal came to $200 + tip without drinks. The whole experience is excellent and highly recommended, but unless you're ballin' only reserved for special occasions. When making reservations, make sure to tell them it's someone's birthday even if it's not. You get a extra free dessert on top of the complementary assorted bites and the pastry they give the ladies to take home. Including the two desserts if you decide to choose as one of the courses, that's FIVE desserts in one night. Can't go wrong with that. The only sad thing is that the meal takes up to 3 hours...and by that time Purple Kow is closed =[.

usually I prefer Italian only places, but this place is great! Only gripe is the parking is sparce. Note to all my readers with exotics, keep them at home, UberLux your way over. If you live in SF this place is an icon for a reason. FANTASITICO!

    I've only been to this PRISTINE EXPENSIVE restaurant once in my entire life. It was several years back, on my birthday. My brother had made reservations a few weeks prior to December 13th, because this place is very high in demand, despite the fact that it is VERY PRICEY up the ARSE!

    The service of course is just timed neatly and precisely, like some choreographed dance that's been practiced to utter perfection. Even if it's fake, it's just nice, because the price is so expensive, that if the service missed a beat, they'll probably receive a silent beating at the end! :P

    It's my birthday, and this time I don't need to cry. I'm well taken care of, and I'm not the one to pay the bill! SWELL!

Everyone looks like they're going to pose for the Hollywood lights and cameras, and they speak with such: 'Oh me oh my, this is just heavenly... Oh yes, we're going to the Hamptons this spring, and yes my son from Princeton will be joining us... Oh yes, England is on our list too! Ha ha ha!... Oh that's just divine! Where on earth did you buy such pearls!...' You know, conversations that you just don't hear everyday, unless you're always surrounded with such wealth. It's not that I don't appreciate the opportunity to eat at such pristine places, with plates filled with delicious artwork, it's just another world of the many worlds that exist today.

    I see and feel all the worlds out there, and it's just strangely amazing how one place, this circle we all live in, has such crazy disparities and similarities... as long as I keep focus on what truly matters, it gets easier for me to remain rooted within the one that matters the most. I suppose, I want and need to experience them all, to find what I'm truly seeking.

    All and all, I'm grateful that my brother made reservations at Gary Danko, because his intention was good... 'I love my sister, and I want her to see and eat and feel PRECIOUS.' So, even when dressed in my comfy sporty sweats, I got to eat and dine at one of the best! Go to Gary Danko at least once in your life, if you haven't yet!

    ** Part 2 of 2** (specific dish reviews)

    * Amuse-bouche: Cucumber tomato soup.
    - Delicious! Loved this. Great interplay of flavors, w/ a dallop of sour cream & chives, & some diced tomato/cucumber sauce in the middle. The tartness of the tomatoes went really well w/ the heavier cucumber puree soup (a slight sweet taste).

    * Glazed Oysters w/ Osetra Caviar, Zucchini & Lettuce Cream
    - Delicious! Loved this! I have never had more rich & flavorful oysters. They soak these in a specially made fish sauce (we questioned the hell out of the servers to figure out what in the world made these oysters so awesome).
    - The caviar added a much needed sharp contrast to the heavy, rich oysters & sauce (which were awesome - but you do need a counter to these flavors), being lighter & having a slight tang.

    * Risotto w/ Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Peas, Corn, & Roasted Tomatoes
    - A very impressive app. You get a giant helping & it's steaming hot when it comes out. The lobster is wonderful.
    - However for me personally, the risotto was a little undercooked (a personal issue. Both my friends thought it was perfect. I prefer it more mushy for lack of a better word, do go w/ the heavy/creamy texture of the dish as a whole. I'm just being picky though - this is quite a delicious app.

    * Seared Sonoma Foie Gras w/ Caramelized Red Onions & Cherries
    - The most well-balanced of the apps we had.
    - The caramelized onions give it a sharp tart flavor & the cherries a hint of sweetness.
    - Those countered well w/ Â the heaviness of the foie gras, which was perfectly seared w/ just a perfect hint of charring.

    * Seared Sea Scallops w/ Asparagus-Pea Puree, Pickled Radish, Spring Onions & Sauce Marechal
    - Really well done, a hint of charring yet raw in the middle, w/ a very tender & homogenous texture (my friend said this is the best scallops she's ever had. I believe her).
    - The sauce is savory while the peas & puree added a great sweetness.

    * Roast Main Lobster w/ Potato Puree, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn & Tarragon
    - Delicious!! Certainly a very heavy, creamy dish, & everything is wonderful - the potato puree is so smooth & the sauce is extremely rich.
    - I'm not usually a big fan of lobster but this dish definitely turned me around to that. The tail has a delectable crunch & the claw is so tender & soft.

    * Quail Stuffed w/ Foie Gras, Mushroom & quinoa, Braised artichokes, Peas, Prosciutto, & Olive Butter
    - First disappointment of the night. While everything sounds good on paper, I don't think the ingredients were balanced well or cooked to their best.
    - The mushroom was extremely heavy in flavor - there was way too much of this. There was not enough foie gras because all three of us could not taste it at all. There was too little quinoa, which could've added a great grainy texture to the filling, & it didn't add much to the dish. The prosciutto was steamed or something - no texture or much flavor to it. Sames goes to the artichokes, very lacking in flavor.
    - The quail itself probably had the best quality meat, being fairly tender & moist, of our three entrees. But it was ruined by all the other ingredients that really weren't balanced well.

    * Moroccan Spiced Squab w/ Raisins, Almonds, Chermoula & Orange-Cumin Carrots
    - Loved Â loved loved the sweet/nutty flavor of the stuffing. It tasted like delicious couscous & was wonderful.
    - However the meat was extremely gamey, & even though it was cooked rare to medium-rare, it was extremely tough to eat. They shouldve given us steak knives as this was extremely difficult to cut w/ regular table knives.
    - I should say that our server did recommend other dishes over this because of the very thing above - the meat being very tough & gamey & not for everyone.

    * Lemon Pepper Duck Breast w/ Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive & Cherries
    - GIANT disappointment. The duck was extremely dry & too tough. Once again we needed steak knives to cut apart the meat.
    - A big reason we chose this was for the lemon flavor, but we could not taste this at all!
    - The endives are steamed/boiled - soft & flavorless. The duck hash had a little more savory flavor & had more tender/moist meat, but really was nothing special.

    * Baked Chocolate Souffle w/ Two Sauces
    - This is apparently THE dessert to get, & it was good, but not extremely amazing. It's fairly light & SO fresh out of the oven that the heavy sauces kind of melt the insides of the cake so it dissolves into the sauce. The chocolate, while dark & good, totally overcomes the white (vanilla?) sauce so you can't taste nor see it.

    * Free: Lemon souffle cake (for our anniversary)
    - Now this was great! Loved the tart flavor of the lemon, that it was served cold, & the heavier yet jelly-like soft texture of the cake.

    * Free: Cookie sampler plate
    - Nice assortment - some good dark chocolates as well as lemony tart like items.

    *Free: Banana cake
    - LOVED it! Extremely moist, w/ Â a wonderful sweet cream cheese in the middle.

    ** Part 1 of 2** (ambiance, service, menu must-haves)

    Sorry to take up 2 reviews but there is just too much to say! I will follow up with an update review specifically on the food.

    AMBIANCE:
    All of us agreed - we felt like we were in a cruise ship. Not a hip new one. One of those lines that are tacky and haven't been redecorated since the mid-90's at the very latest. The windows are just black, you can't see outside at all. They totally overdo the mirrors all over the place. There are these paintings and flowers that I'm sure are meant to be "modern" and "trendy" but just seem overdone and in poor taste. And the plants in the corners all have this ugly orange lighting behind it.

    Not that I should judge the customer base, but it was definitely a more mature crowd, probably the "older money" crowd of the city. I felt out of place with a small group of 20-somethings who are splurging on a nice dinner, whereas everyone else probably spends like this on a regular basis.

    The servers (poor things) are forced to wear these ugly suits, even the women! While I'm sure they are expensive and perfectly fitted, they just make everyone look uncomfortable stuffy.

    SERVICE:
    Great, great service. There was someone to take care of everything. They timed our dishes really well, giving us space to digest between courses. I love the little things like how they wait til one of our party members is back from the restroom to bring out the next course, how they fold our napkins if we leave the table, and that when we left, there were two gentlemen holding our coats waiting for us at the door! They helped us put on our jackets and offered to hail a cab. Wonderful. Plus they were very accommodating about us changing one of the desserts to an appetizer at the last minute.

    FOOD:
    We realized a little too late that while Gary Danko does seafood INCREDIBLY well, he doesnt' do much else well. And we made the mistake of ordering a quail, duck, and squab entree - all very similar meats, and all not in the least impressive. In fact, we should've sent back the duck in retrospect, it was that bad. Even their most popular dessert, the chocolate souffle, I feel I've had better at just about every other New American restaurant in the city (Range, for example, where I'd just gone two days earlier).

    The must haves on the menu: Oysters w/ Caviar, Ricotta w/ Lobster, Roast Maine Lobster. All were delicious.

    Do NOT order: Â Lemon Pepper Duck Breast (way too dry!), Moroccan Spice Squab (way way way too gamey and tough. Our server did warn us of this - it's definitely not for everyone. Though the raisins/ almonds/ cumin it came with was quite good).

    For my 800th review it was only fitting that I review Gary Danko (GD).

    I've gone by GD many times on the cable car on my way home in Russian Hill. I'll be honest and say that the Michelin star buzz is a bit beyond me. Over the years I have enjoyed some amazing restaurants in SF but this is my first time at a restaurant that is such an institution.

    My girlfriend was generous enough to take me here for my 30th birthday. It did seem that a good number of people dining were here for a special occasion.

    The first thing I noticed was that the service was superb. This is the one differentiator between restaurants with great food that are more reasonably priced. Everything at GD seemed perfectly choreographed and executed. It's the difference between a highly skilled NCAA division 1 athlete and an gold medal olympian. Both great but one has honed their craft to a remarkable degree.

    My favorite dish was the lobster risotto. One of the best dishes I have ever had.

    I also had the pork belly which I found to be above average but didn't blow away other pork belly I've had.

    I also enjoyed the scallops. Some of the best I've had.

    What I most liked about GD is that you have a 3, 4 and 5 course option and you get to decide what items you eat. While this seems to be common sense it has not been my experience dining in nicer restaurants; usually the courses are determined for you.

    The bread and butter to start were amazing. Simple but amazing.

    For the desserts we had the creme brulee trio and souffle. Both were excellent.

    What can I say that hasn't been said? Gary Danko is worth a visit for a special occasion. While you can cab or drive here, taking the cable car at night was a nice touch as it drops you off right in front.

    Thank you, Sofia H!

We ate early and took in the sunset of the bridge and walked around to settle our over full bellies. My hesitancy about giving it 5 stars was the foie gras had too many veins running through it, so cutting around them was not what I would expect from a place like this...but don't get me wrong...I cut every little morsel out of that bugger and ate the whole damn thing while mopping up the sauce with the bread my friendly neighborhood bread pusher was placing on my plate. Drooling thinking about it...

    All in all a great place to eat and be served like a king. The service was the best thing about this place. We are a bit spoiled, so I was expecting to be wowed, which wasn't the case with the food. If I had to do over again, I would have gone somewhere else.

    Two birds with one stone. Wanted something special for the lady so decided to come here for a combined anniversary + early valentine's dinner lol. Made reservations a little more than a month in advance and the earliest opening on a Thursday night was for 9 PM. The reservation process was quick and easy and they called the week of the reservation to confirm. Was a little worried about getting rushed to finish dinner since the restaurant closes at 10, but we stayed until almost midnight and the staff were nothing but courteous.

    Parking was a breeze with multiple spaces open around the corner. Saved on the valet and the embarrassment of having them park my trusty but well aged civic.

    From the many yelp reviews we decided to do the four course option, but we were fairly stuffed by the time the third course came around, yet we savored and ate every single bite, including both souffles. Yes we got both of them haha.

    What we ordered:

    First Course
    Crispy Farm Egg
    Lobster Risotto

    Second Course
    Roast Maine Lobster
    Seared Sea Scallops

    Third Course
    Seared Filet of Beef
    Lemon Pepper Duck Breast

    Fourth Course
    Strawberry Souffle
    Chocolate Souffle

    Besides the souffles, the stars of the night were the lobster risotto and the scallops. This is hands down the best scallops I ever had, out shinning the ones at Alexander's.

    We were both disappointed by the crispy farm egg, especially when it was hyped up by so many reviews here. An odd note is that they give you a butter knife to cut the filet unless you specifically ask for a steak knife.

    At the end, the meal came to $200 + tip without drinks. The whole experience is excellent and highly recommended, but unless you're ballin' only reserved for special occasions.

    When making reservations, make sure to tell them it's someone's birthday even if it's not. You get a extra free dessert on top of the complementary assorted bites and the pastry they give the ladies to take home. Including the two desserts if you decide to choose as one of the courses, that's FIVE desserts in one night. Can't go wrong with that. The only sad thing is that the meal takes up to 3 hours...and by that time Purple Kow is closed =[.
